03972nam a22006615i 9781501743061DE-B159720190904122446.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190904s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017430617 a10.7591/97815017430612doi  a(DE-B1597)533903  a(OCoLC)1121053918  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0070002bisacsh1 aReinhardt, Mark, eauthor.14aThe Art of Being Free :bTaking Liberties with Tocquevile, Marx, and Arendt /cMark Reinhardt. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContestations00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: The Art of Being Free -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Making Space for Politics -- t2. Disturbing Democracy: Reading (in) the Gaps between Tocqueville's America and Ours -- t3. (Con)Founding Democracy: Containment, Evasion, Appropriation -- t4. Reading Freedom, Writing Marx: From the Politics of Production to the Production of Politics -- t5. Acting (Up) in Publics: Mobile Spaces, Plural Worlds -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe "art of being free" is an essential part of democracy. It involves, Mark Reinhardt believes, bringing into being the multiple spaces in and practices through which individuals and groups help to constitute their lives, their selves, their worlds. Americans are presently witnessing a contraction of officially sanctioned spaces for citizen action. It is now crucial, Reinhardt argues, to identify ways of opening new spaces for the direct practice of democratic politics.Reinhardt treats the writings of Alexis de Tocqueville, Karl Marx, and Hannah Arendt as exemplary sources for an expansion of political possibility. These writers indicate where and how the new spaces can be brought into being, and they reveal acts of making space as some of the prime moments of politics. Reinhardt's extended readings of these writers, never previously treated together, are quite unlike the familiar understandings of their thought. "Taking liberties," he brings the literary and political sensibility usually associated with postmodernism to a sympathetic if critical encounter with eminently modern thinkers. The result is a strong and idiosyncratic book, accessible and stylish, that mixes acute readings of canonical thinkers with more practical applications and illustrations. Reinhardt combines attention to textual detail and nuance with concern for contemporary politics, discussing as an unusually inventive example the AIDS activist group ACT UP.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Sep 2019) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Free Will & Determinism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501743061423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501743061.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG